The theoretical capabilities of the aforementioned hardware can only be realized through robust control architectures that ensure deterministic execution.
\textbf{Middleware and Real-Time Determinism:} The transition from \textit{ROS 1} to \textit{ROS 2} marks a fundamental shift in robotic middleware. While ROS 1 relies on TCP/IP with inherent latency, ROS 2 employs the Data Distribution Service (DDS) standard, supporting Quality of Service (QoS) policies essential for real-time control. For high-frequency loops ($>$1 kHz), shared-memory interfaces and real-time kernels (e.g., PREEMPT\_RT) are mandatory to minimize jitter, ensuring that torque commands are synchronized with sensor feedback.
\textbf{Whole-Body Control (WBC):} For high-DoF floating-base systems, WBC serves as the central optimization engine. It formulates the control problem as a Quadratic Program (QP), solving for joint torques that satisfy a hierarchy of tasks—prioritizing balance and stability constraints above manipulation objectives. Frameworks like \textit{WBC} allow for the seamless integration of mobile base, torso, and arm motions.
\textbf{Model Predictive Control (MPC):} To handle the system's dynamics and actuator limits over a future horizon, MPC is employed. Unlike instantaneous WBC, MPC optimizes trajectories over a time window, allowing the robot to "foresee" dynamic limits and plan momentum-based maneuvers. The combination of high-frequency WBC (for stabilization) and low-frequency MPC (for planning) constitutes the state-of-the-art architecture for dynamic embodied intelligence.